# Backend Standards

## TypeScript
- Strict mode always on
- No `any` (use `unknown` if needed)
- No non-null assertions (`!`) without comment
- Prefer interfaces for object shapes
- Use `type` for unions/intersections
- Branded types for IDs (UserId, WorkspaceId)

## File Naming
- kebab-case for files: `user-service.ts`
- PascalCase for classes: `UserService`
- camelCase for functions/variables
- UPPER_SNAKE for constants

## Imports
- Absolute imports via tsconfig paths
- Group: std lib → external → internal → relative
- No circular dependencies

## Async
- Always async/await, no raw promises
- Always handle errors (try/catch or .catch)
- No floating promises
- Cancellation via AbortSignal

## Validation
- Zod schemas for ALL external inputs
- Validate at boundary (HTTP, queue, file)
- Internal functions trust types
- DTOs derived from Zod with `z.infer`

## Database
- Drizzle ORM, no raw SQL unless necessary
- Transactions for multi-step writes
- Always include tenant filter
- Use prepared statements
- No N+1 queries (use joins/batching)

## API Design
- RESTful where natural
- Consistent response shape: `{ data, error, meta }`
- Pagination: cursor-based
- Versioning: `/v1/`, `/v2/`
- OpenAPI spec generated from code

## Testing
- Vitest for unit/integration
- Test files: `*.test.ts` next to source
- AAA pattern (Arrange, Act, Assert)
- No mocks for DB (use test DB)
- Mock external services

## Performance
- Cache where appropriate (Redis)
- Batch DB queries
- Stream large responses
- Avoid sync I/O
- Profile before optimizing

## Security
- Never trust client input
- Sanitize before storing
- Escape before rendering
- Use parameterized queries
- Hash sensitive data
- Encrypt at rest

## Comments
- Why, not what
- TODO with ticket reference
- No commented-out code
- JSDoc for public APIs